---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="RINEX">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/protocols">Protocols</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>RINEX</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Protocols · Article 2 of 5</span>
        <h1>RINEX</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          RINEX — Receiver Independent Exchange Format — is the standard for storing and exchanging
          GNSS observation data and navigation messages. If you want to post-process raw GNSS data,
          compute a precise position with PPP, or submit data to a CORS network, you will work with
          RINEX files.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#overview">Overview and purpose</a></li>
          <li><a href="#file-types">File types</a></li>
          <li><a href="#versions">RINEX versions</a></li>
          <li><a href="#observation-file">Observation file structure</a></li>
          <li><a href="#obs-codes">Observation codes</a></li>
          <li><a href="#navigation-file">Navigation file structure</a></li>
          <li><a href="#naming">File naming conventions</a></li>
          <li><a href="#tools">Working with RINEX files</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="overview">Overview and purpose</h2>
      <p>
        Before RINEX (1989), sharing GNSS data between research groups was nearly impossible —
        each receiver manufacturer used a proprietary binary format. RINEX solved this by
        defining a receiver-independent ASCII format that any software could read, regardless
        of which receiver collected the data.
      </p>
      <p>
        RINEX is not a real-time protocol. It is a <strong>file format</strong> for archiving
        and exchanging GNSS data. A receiver logs raw measurements to a proprietary binary
        format in real time, then converts to RINEX for sharing, post-processing or submission
        to data archives like CDDIS (NASA) or IGS.
      </p>

      <div class="use-cases">
        <div class="uc">
          <div class="uc-icon">🔄</div>
          <div class="uc-title">Post-processing</div>
          <div class="uc-desc">Submit RINEX observations to PPP services (CSRS-PPP, APPS) or process with RTKLIB, BERNESE, GIPSY.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="uc">
          <div class="uc-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="uc-title">Data sharing</div>
          <div class="uc-desc">CORS networks archive observations as RINEX. IGS distributes global tracking data in RINEX for orbit/clock computation.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="uc">
          <div class="uc-icon">🔬</div>
          <div class="uc-title">Research</div>
          <div class="uc-desc">GNSS research uses RINEX as the universal input format. Any algorithm development starts with RINEX files.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="uc">
          <div class="uc-icon">📐</div>
          <div class="uc-title">Geodetic survey</div>
          <div class="uc-desc">Static surveys collect RINEX for hours, then process against nearby CORS stations to achieve millimetre accuracy.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="file-types">File types</h2>
      <p>
        A complete RINEX dataset typically consists of multiple files covering different data types:
      </p>

      <div class="file-type-grid">
        <div class="ft-card ft-obs">
          <div class="ft-ext">.rnx / .obs</div>
          <div class="ft-name">Observation file</div>
          <div class="ft-desc">Raw measurements — pseudoranges (code), carrier phases, Doppler and signal strength for every satellite at each epoch. The primary RINEX file type.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ft-card ft-nav">
          <div class="ft-ext">.nav / .rnx</div>
          <div class="ft-name">Navigation file</div>
          <div class="ft-desc">Satellite ephemeris (orbital parameters) and clock corrections decoded from the navigation message. One file can cover all constellations in RINEX 3+.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ft-card ft-met">
          <div class="ft-ext">.met</div>
          <div class="ft-name">Meteorological file</div>
          <div class="ft-desc">Surface meteorological data — temperature, pressure, humidity — collocated with the receiver. Used to improve tropospheric delay modelling.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ft-card ft-clk">
          <div class="ft-ext">.clk</div>
          <div class="ft-name">Clock file</div>
          <div class="ft-desc">High-rate satellite and receiver clock estimates from precise timing analysis. Used in PPP to replace broadcast clock corrections.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="versions">RINEX versions</h2>
      <p>
        RINEX has evolved significantly over 35 years. Understanding which version you have
        matters — parsers and processing software often support only specific versions:
      </p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Version</th>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>Key changes</th>
              <th>Status</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>RINEX 2.11</strong></td>
              <td>2007</td>
              <td>GPS + GLONASS. Separate navigation files per constellation. Widely supported.</td>
              <td>Legacy — still common</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>RINEX 3.04</strong></td>
              <td>2018</td>
              <td>Multi-constellation (GPS, GLONASS, Galileo, BeiDou, QZSS, SBAS). New obs codes. Single mixed navigation file. New naming convention.</td>
              <td>Current standard</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>RINEX 3.05</strong></td>
              <td>2020</td>
              <td>Minor clarifications. NavIC/IRNSS added. L6 signal support for Galileo HAS.</td>
              <td>Current</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>RINEX 4.00</strong></td>
              <td>2021</td>
              <td>Restructured navigation file with record types. Improved handling of SSR-like data and integrity information.</td>
              <td>Emerging</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Practical note:</strong> RINEX 2.11 is still widely produced by older receivers
          and accepted by most processing services. RINEX 3 is required for multi-constellation
          processing, Galileo and BeiDou data. When submitting to IGS or CDDIS, RINEX 3.04 or
          later is preferred.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="observation-file">Observation file structure</h2>
      <p>
        A RINEX observation file has two sections: a <strong>header</strong> (metadata) and
        a <strong>data body</strong> (measurements at each epoch).
      </p>

      <h3>Header</h3>
      <p>
        The header is fixed-format, column-aligned ASCII. Each line has a label in columns 61–80.
        Key header records:
      </p>

      <div class="rinex-header">
        <div class="rh-line">
          <div class="rh-content">     3.04           OBSERVATION DATA    M (Mixed)        RINEX VERSION / TYPE</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rh-line">
          <div class="rh-content">teqc  2019Feb25                         20190301 000000UTC PGM / RUN BY / DATE</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rh-line">
          <div class="rh-content">ALGO                                                        MARKER NAME</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rh-line">
          <div class="rh-content">  4789440.8430   176955.3690  4194576.7740                 APPROX POSITION XYZ</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rh-line rh-important">
          <div class="rh-content">G    8 C1C L1C D1C S1C C2W L2W D2W S2W                  SYS / # / OBS TYPES</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rh-line rh-important">
          <div class="rh-content">E    4 C1C L1C C5Q L5Q                                    SYS / # / OBS TYPES</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rh-line">
          <div class="rh-content">  30.000                                                   INTERVAL</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rh-line">
          <div class="rh-content">  2019     3     1     0     0    0.0000000                TIME OF FIRST OBS</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rh-line">
          <div class="rh-content">                                                            END OF HEADER</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The <code>SYS / # / OBS TYPES</code> record is critical — it defines which observation
        types are in the file for each constellation. In the example above, GPS (<code>G</code>)
        has 8 observation types and Galileo (<code>E</code>) has 4.
      </p>

      <h3>Data body</h3>
      <p>
        After the header, the file contains measurement epochs. Each epoch starts with a header
        line giving the time and satellite list, followed by one line of observations per satellite:
      </p>

      <div class="rinex-data">
        <div class="rd-line rd-epoch">
          <div class="rd-content">&gt; 2019  3  1  0  0  0.0000000  0  8</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">Epoch: year mon day h m s, flag=0 (OK), 8 satellites</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">G01  23274318.300   122316543.890   -2045.314          44.000  ...</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">GPS PRN 1: C1C, L1C, D1C, S1C, ...</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">G04  21456789.123   112765432.100   -1234.567          42.500  ...</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">GPS PRN 4</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">E11  22345678.456   117543210.789    -987.654          40.000  ...</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">Galileo PRN 11</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="obs-codes">Observation codes</h2>
      <p>
        RINEX 3 uses a three-character observation code to identify each measurement type.
        The three characters encode:
      </p>

      <div class="obs-code-anatomy">
        <div class="oc-char">
          <div class="oc-val">C</div>
          <div class="oc-pos">Character 1</div>
          <div class="oc-meaning">Observation type</div>
          <div class="oc-options">C=code/pseudorange · L=carrier phase · D=Doppler · S=signal strength</div>
        </div>
        <div class="oc-char">
          <div class="oc-val">1</div>
          <div class="oc-pos">Character 2</div>
          <div class="oc-meaning">Frequency band</div>
          <div class="oc-options">1=L1/E1/B1 · 2=L2/B2 · 5=L5/E5a/B2a · 6=E6/B3 · 7=E5b/B2b · 8=E5</div>
        </div>
        <div class="oc-char">
          <div class="oc-val">C</div>
          <div class="oc-pos">Character 3</div>
          <div class="oc-meaning">Attribute (signal/code)</div>
          <div class="oc-options">C=C/A · W=P(Y) · Q=pilot · I=data · X=I+Q combined · S=M-code</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Code</th>
              <th>Meaning</th>
              <th>Typical use</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>C1C</code></td>
              <td>GPS L1 C/A code pseudorange</td>
              <td>Standard single-frequency positioning</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>L1C</code></td>
              <td>GPS L1 C/A carrier phase</td>
              <td>RTK, PPP carrier phase observation</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>D1C</code></td>
              <td>GPS L1 C/A Doppler</td>
              <td>Velocity estimation, cycle-slip detection</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>S1C</code></td>
              <td>GPS L1 C/A signal strength (dB-Hz)</td>
              <td>Quality monitoring, masking</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>C5Q</code></td>
              <td>GPS L5 / Galileo E5a pilot code pseudorange</td>
              <td>Dual-frequency ionosphere-free combination</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>L5Q</code></td>
              <td>GPS L5 / Galileo E5a pilot carrier phase</td>
              <td>Dual-frequency RTK/PPP</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>C1C</code> (Galileo)</td>
              <td>Galileo E1 OS code pseudorange</td>
              <td>Same code, different constellation</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>C7Q</code></td>
              <td>Galileo E5b / BeiDou B2b pilot pseudorange</td>
              <td>Triple-frequency processing</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="navigation-file">Navigation file structure</h2>
      <p>
        The RINEX navigation file contains satellite ephemeris records decoded from the navigation
        message. Each record provides the Keplerian elements and perturbation parameters needed
        to compute the satellite's position at any time within the ephemeris validity period.
      </p>

      <p>
        A GPS navigation record example (RINEX 3, 8 lines per record):
      </p>

      <div class="rinex-data">
        <div class="rd-line rd-epoch">
          <div class="rd-content">G01 2019 03 01 00 00 00-1.659572124481e-04-8.412668087684e-12 0.000000000000e+00</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">PRN, epoch, a0 (clock bias), a1 (freq drift), a2 (drift rate)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">     1.300000000000e+01 4.234375000000e+01 4.678648742924e-09-2.785678029083e+00</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">IODE, Crs, Δn, M0</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">     1.396052539349e-06 1.379120116681e-02 5.327537655830e-06 5.153696712494e+03</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">Cuc, e (eccentricity), Cus, √a</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">     3.456000000000e+05-2.421438694000e-07 3.004530895000e+00-1.862645149231e-08</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">toe, Cic, Ω0, Cis</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">     9.741855893934e-01 2.186875000000e+02-1.204148753480e+00-8.012729204117e-09</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">i0, Crc, ω, Ω̇</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">     9.634413133217e-12 0.000000000000e+00 2.041000000000e+03 0.000000000000e+00</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">İ, spare, GPS week, L2 P flag</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">     2.000000000000e+00 0.000000000000e+00 5.587935447693e-09 0.000000000000e+00</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">SV accuracy, SV health, TGD, IODC</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rd-line">
          <div class="rd-content">     3.456060000000e+05 4.000000000000e+00</div>
          <div class="rd-comment">Transmission time, fit interval (hours)</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="naming">File naming conventions</h2>
      <p>
        RINEX 2 and RINEX 3 use different naming conventions. RINEX 3 introduced a long filename
        format that encodes more metadata:
      </p>

      <div class="naming-grid">
        <div class="naming-card">
          <div class="naming-version">RINEX 2 (short name)</div>
          <div class="naming-example">algo0010.19o</div>
          <div class="naming-parts">
            <div class="np"><span>algo</span><span>4-char station ID</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>001</span><span>Day of year (001 = Jan 1)</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>0</span><span>File sequence (0 = daily)</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>.19</span><span>Year (2019)</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>o</span><span>Type: o=obs, n=GPS nav, g=GLONASS nav, p=mixed nav</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="naming-card">
          <div class="naming-version">RINEX 3 (long name)</div>
          <div class="naming-example">ALGO00CAN_R_20190010000_01D_30S_MO.rnx</div>
          <div class="naming-parts">
            <div class="np"><span>ALGO00CAN</span><span>9-char station (name + monument + country)</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>R</span><span>Data source: R=receiver, S=stream, U=unknown</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>20190010000</span><span>Start time: year + DOY + hour (0000 = 00:00)</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>01D</span><span>Duration: 01 Day</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>30S</span><span>Sample rate: 30 Seconds</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>MO</span><span>Content: M=Mixed constellation, O=Observation</span></div>
            <div class="np"><span>.rnx</span><span>Extension (compressed: .crx or .gz)</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 -->
      <h2 id="tools">Working with RINEX files</h2>
      <p>
        Several free tools are essential when working with RINEX data:
      </p>

      <div class="tools-grid">
        <div class="tool-card">
          <div class="tool-name">RTKLIB</div>
          <div class="tool-desc">Open-source GNSS processing suite. Converts proprietary binary to RINEX (RTKCONV), post-processes baselines (RTKPOST), runs PPP. The most widely used open-source GNSS toolkit.</div>
          <a href="https://rtklib.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="tool-link">rtklib.com →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card">
          <div class="tool-name">gfzrnx</div>
          <div class="tool-desc">GFZ Potsdam RINEX file manipulation tool. Converts between RINEX versions, splices files, extracts constellations, repairs headers. The standard tool for RINEX file management.</div>
          <a href="https://www.gfz-potsdam.de/en/section/space-geodetic-techniques/software/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="tool-link">GFZ →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card">
          <div class="tool-name">teqc</div>
          <div class="tool-desc">UNAVCO translation, editing and quality checking tool. Converts many proprietary formats to RINEX, performs quality checks (multipath, SNR, cycle slips). Legacy but still widely used.</div>
          <a href="https://www.unavco.org/software/data-processing/teqc/teqc.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="tool-link">UNAVCO →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-card">
          <div class="tool-name">NRCan CSRS-PPP</div>
          <div class="tool-desc">Submit a RINEX observation file, receive a PPP solution using IGS precise products. Free. Supports static and kinematic processing. 2 cm accuracy for long static sessions.</div>
          <a href="https://webapp.csrs-scrs.nrcan-rncan.gc.ca/geod/tools-outils/ppp.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="tool-link">NRCan →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 9 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📁</div>
          <div class="summary-title">File format, not protocol</div>
          <div class="summary-body">RINEX is for archiving and exchanging data, not real-time streaming. Receivers log proprietary binary in real time and convert to RINEX for sharing or post-processing.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📋</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Observation + navigation</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Raw measurements go in the observation file (.rnx). Satellite ephemeris goes in the navigation file (.nav). Both are needed for standalone post-processing.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔤</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Obs codes define what's measured</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Three-character codes (e.g. C1C, L5Q) identify each measurement precisely. The header's SYS / OBS TYPES record lists which codes the file contains.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔢</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Use RINEX 3 for multi-constellation</div>
          <div class="summary-body">RINEX 2 only covers GPS and GLONASS. Any file containing Galileo, BeiDou or other constellations must be RINEX 3.03 or later.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/protocols/nmea-0183" class="nav-prev">← NMEA 0183</a>
        <a href="/learn/protocols/rtcm" class="nav-next">RTCM →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>IGS/RTCM-SC104 (2018). RINEX Version 3.04. <a href="https://files.igs.org/pub/data/format/rinex304.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IGS →</a></li>
          <li>Gurtner, W. & Estey, L. (2007). RINEX: The Receiver Independent Exchange Format Version 2.11. <a href="https://files.igs.org/pub/data/format/rinex211.txt" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IGS →</a></li>
          <li>RTKLIB v2.4.3 Manual. <a href="https://www.rtklib.com/prog/manual_2.4.2.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rtklib.com →</a></li>
          <li>IGS Data Centre — CDDIS. <a href="https://cddis.nasa.gov/Data_and_Derived_Products/GNSS/GNSS_data_and_product_archive.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NASA CDDIS →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  h3 { font-size: 17px; font-weight: 600; margin: 28px 0 12px; }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }
